2. Overall Description
2.1 Product Perspective
ChopNow is a new, self-contained product designed to address the unique challenges of food waste and food insecurity in Africa. It is not a replacement for existing food delivery systems but rather a complementary platform focused on sustainability and social impact. The system will interface with mobile operating systems (Android and iOS), payment gateways, and potentially third-party mapping services for location-based functionalities. The core components include a mobile application for consumers, a mobile/web application for vendors, and a robust backend server with a database.
2.2 Product Functions
The major functions of ChopNow include: * Vendor Management: Registration, profile creation, meal listing (with quantity, price, and pickup times), and order fulfillment. * Consumer Features: User registration, browsing available meals, filtering by location/cuisine/price, placing orders, and secure payment. * Order Management: Real-time order tracking, status updates, and cancellation handling. * Notification System: Alerts for new meal listings, order confirmations, and pickup reminders. * Payment Processing: Integration with local mobile money and card payment systems. * Rating and Review System: For both vendors and consumers to provide feedback. * Reporting and Analytics: For vendors to track sales and for administrators to monitor platform performance and social impact metrics.
2.3 User Classes and Characteristics
ChopNow will serve two primary user classes:
Consumers:
Characteristics: Low-income families, students, and individuals seeking affordable meal options. They are typically mobile-savvy but may have limited disposable income. They prioritize affordability, convenience, and food quality.
Importance: High, as they represent the demand side and beneficiaries of the food rescue mission.
Vendors:
Characteristics: Local restaurants, bakeries, cafes, and food stalls with surplus food. They are motivated to reduce waste, recover costs, and reach new customer segments. They require an easy-to-use interface for listing meals and managing orders.
Importance: High, as they provide the supply of discounted meals and are crucial for the platform's inventory.
2.4 Operating Environment
The ChopNow platform will operate in the following environment: * Hardware Platform: Mobile devices (smartphones and tablets) running Android and iOS. Backend servers will run on cloud infrastructure (e.g., AWS, Google Cloud, Azure). * Operating Systems: Android (version 8.0 and above), iOS (version 12.0 and above), Linux for backend servers. * Software Components: Database (e.g., PostgreSQL, MongoDB), payment gateway APIs (e.g., M-Pesa, Stripe), mapping APIs (e.g., Google Maps), notification services (e.g., Firebase Cloud Messaging). * Network: Requires stable internet connectivity (3G, 4G, Wi-Fi) for real-time updates and transactions.
2.5 Design and Implementation Constraints
Regulatory Policies: Adherence to local food safety regulations and data privacy laws (e.g., GDPR-like regulations in some African countries).
Hardware Limitations: Optimization for diverse mobile devices, including those with lower specifications and varying screen sizes.
Network Latency: Design must account for potentially inconsistent internet connectivity in some regions, ensuring offline capabilities where feasible and robust error handling.
Security Considerations: Robust security measures for user data, payment information, and transaction integrity.
Technology Stack: Preference for open-source technologies where possible to minimize licensing costs. Mobile development using cross-platform frameworks (e.g., React Native, Flutter) to ensure wider reach and faster development.
Payment Integration: Integration with multiple local mobile money and card payment solutions prevalent in target African markets.
2.6 User Documentation
The following user documentation components will be delivered: * Consumer Mobile App Guide: In-app tutorials and a comprehensive help section covering registration, browsing, ordering, payment, and support. * Vendor Web/Mobile App Guide: A detailed guide for vendors on profile setup, meal listing, order management, and payout procedures. * FAQ Section: A publicly accessible FAQ section on the ChopNow website and within the apps. * Customer Support Portal: An online portal for submitting tickets and accessing further assistance.
2.7 Assumptions and Dependencies
Assumptions:

Users (both consumers and vendors) will have access to smartphones and internet connectivity.

Vendors are willing to sell surplus food at discounted prices. Consumers are willing to purchase surplus food through a digital platform.

Reliable third-party payment gateway services will be available and integrated.

Local regulations will permit the sale of surplus food through such a platform.


Dependencies:

Availability and stability of mobile network infrastructure.
Integration with external payment processing APIs.
Integration with mapping and location services APIs.
Compliance with evolving local and international data
protection and food safety regulations.
3. External Interface Requirements
3.1 User Interfaces
The ChopNow platform will feature two primary user interfaces:
Consumer Mobile Application:
Layout: Intuitive, clean, and mobile-first design with easy navigation.
Key Screens: Home (featured meals, search), Browse/Filter, Meal Details, Cart, Checkout, Order History, User Profile, Notifications.
GUI Standards: Adherence to Material Design (Android) and Human Interface Guidelines (iOS) for native look and feel. Consistent branding and color palette (e.g., warm, inviting colors).
Elements: Standard buttons (e.g.,
Add to Cart, Checkout, Help), search bars, filters, image carousels for meal photos. * Error Messages: Clear, concise, and actionable error messages are displayed prominently. * Accessibility: Support for screen readers and adjustable font sizes.
Vendor Mobile/Web Application:

Layout: Responsive design suitable for both mobile and web browsers, focusing on efficiency for managing inventory and orders.
Key Screens: Dashboard (overview of sales, active listings, pending orders), Add/Edit Meal, Order List, Order Details, Payouts, Profile Settings.
GUI Standards: Consistent with consumer app branding, but optimized for business operations. Data visualization for sales trends.
Elements: Forms for meal creation, tables for order management, status toggles for meal availability, and secure login/logout.
Error Messages: Real-time validation feedback on forms, clear notifications for failed transactions or order issues.
Accessibility: Keyboard navigation support for the web interface, clear visual hierarchy.
3.2 Hardware Interfaces
ChopNow will primarily interface with standard mobile device hardware and cloud server infrastructure:
Mobile Devices:
Touchscreens: For user interaction (tapping, swiping, pinch-to-zoom). Cameras: For vendors to upload meal photos.
GPS/Location Services: For matching consumers with nearby vendors and for delivery/pickup point identification.
Microphone/Speaker: For potential in-app customer support or voice commands (future enhancement).
Vibration Motor: For notifications.
Backend Servers:
Processors: Multi-core CPUs for handling concurrent requests and data processing.
Memory: Sufficient RAM for database operations and application server processes.
Storage: High-speed SSDs for database and application data storage, with redundancy for data integrity.
Network Interfaces: High-bandwidth network cards for efficient data transfer.
3.3 Software Interfaces
ChopNow will integrate with several third-party software components and APIs:
Operating Systems: Android OS (Google APIs) and iOS (Apple APIs) for mobile application functionality.
Payment Gateways:
Mobile Money APIs: Integration with popular African mobile money services (e.g., M-Pesa, MTN Mobile Money, Airtel Money) for secure transactions.
Card Payment APIs: Integration with international payment processors (e.g., Stripe, Paystack) for credit/debit card payments.
Mapping Services: Google Maps API or OpenStreetMap API for location-based services, displaying vendor locations, and calculating distances.
Notification Services: Firebase Cloud Messaging (FCM) for push notifications to both consumers and vendors.
Database Management System: PostgreSQL or MongoDB for data storage and retrieval.
Cloud Services: AWS, Google Cloud Platform, or Azure for hosting backend services, databases, and storage.
Analytics Tools: Google Analytics or similar for tracking user behavior and platform performance.
Email Service Providers: SendGrid or Mailgun for transactional emails (e.g., order confirmations, password resets).
3.4 Communications Interfaces
The ChopNow platform will rely on various communication protocols and standards:
Internet Protocols:
HTTP/HTTPS: For secure client-server communication between mobile apps and backend services.
TCP/IP: Underlying network protocol for all internet-based communication.
Data Formats:
JSON: Primary data interchange format for API requests and responses.
XML: Potentially for integration with legacy systems or specific payment gateways.
Security Protocols:
SSL/TLS: For encrypting all data in transit, ensuring secure communication. OAuth 2.0: For secure API authentication and authorization.
Communication Standards:
RESTful APIs: For well-defined and stateless communication between components.
Push Notifications: Via FCM for real-time alerts.
Data Transfer Rates: Optimized for varying network conditions, with mechanisms for data compression and efficient caching to minimize bandwidth usage.
Synchronization Mechanisms: Real-time data synchronization for order status updates, meal availability, and location tracking.
4. System Feature 1: User Authentication and Profile Management

Description: This feature allows users (both consumers and vendors) to register, log in, manage their profiles, and securely access the ChopNow platform. It includes functionalities for creating accounts, password management, and viewing/editing personal or business information.


4.1 System Feature 1: User Registration and Authentication

ReqID
Requiremet
Description
FR1.1
User Registration
The system shall allow new users to register as either a Consumer or Vendor by providing a valid email address/phone number and password.
FR1.2
Verification
The system shall send a verification link/code to the user’s registered email/phone number upon registration.
FR1.3
Login
The system shall allow registered users to log in using their verified credentials.
FR1.4
Password Recovery
The system shall provide a Forgot Password functionality to reset passwords via email/phone verification.
FR1.5
Consumer Profile
The system shall allow consumers to view and edit their personal profile information (e.g., name, contact details, profile picture, preferred payment methods).
FR1.6
Vendor Profile
The system shall allow vendors to view and edit their business profile information (e.g., business name, address, contact details, operating hours, food hygiene certifications, bank details for payouts).
FR1.7
Credential Storage
The system shall securely store user credentials using industry-standard encryption.
FR1.8
Password Policy
The system shall enforce strong password policies (e.g., minimum length, combination of characters).





4.2 System Feature 2: Meal Listing and Discovery
Req ID
Requirement
Description
FR2.1
Create Listings
The system shall allow authenticated vendors to create new meal listings, including meal name, description, original price, discounted price, quantity available, pickup/delivery options, and available pickup times.
FR2.2
Upload Images
The system shall allow vendors to upload high-quality images for each meal listing.
FR2.3
Update/Remove Listings
The system shall allow vendors to update or remove existing meal listings.
FR2.4
Display Listings
The system shall display available meal listings to consumers based on their current location or a specified location.
FR2.5
Filters
The system shall allow consumers to filter meal listings by cuisine type, price range, dietary restrictions, and distance from their location.
FR2.6
Search
The system shall allow consumers to search for specific meals or vendors.
FR2.7
Meal Details
The system shall display detailed information for each meal listing, including vendor name, rating, meal description, prices, quantity, and pickup instructions.
FR2.8
Real-Time Availability
The system shall provide a mechanism for vendors to mark meals as sold out or unavailable in real-time.



4.3 System Feature 3: Order Placement and Management

Req ID
Requirement
Description
FR3.1
Add to Cart
The system shall allow authenticated consumers to add available meals to a shopping cart.
FR3.2
Cart Review
The system shall allow consumers to review their shopping cart before checkout.
FR3.3
Payment Selection
The system shall allow consumers to select a preferred payment method (e.g., mobile money, card payment) during checkout.
FR3.4
Payment Processing
The system shall process secure payments for orders.
FR3.5
Order Confirmation
The system shall generate an order confirmation for the consumer upon successful payment.
FR3.6
Vendor Notification
The system shall notify the vendor immediately upon a new order placement.
FR3.7
Order View
The system shall allow vendors to view a list of pending, accepted, and completed orders.
FR3.8
Accept/Reject Orders
The system shall allow vendors to accept or reject an order.
FR3.9
Order Status Updates
The system shall allow vendors to update the status of an order (e.g., Preparing, Ready for Pickup, Picked Up).
FR3.10
Consumer Notifications
The system shall notify consumers of changes in their order status in real-time.
FR3.11
Order History
The system shall provide an order history for both consumers and vendors.


4.4 System Feature 4: Notifications and Communication

Req ID
Requirement
Description
FR4.1
Consumer Notifications
The system shall send push notifications to consumers for new meal listings from their favorite vendors or in their preferred area.
FR4.2
Order Notifications
The system shall send push notifications to consumers for order confirmations, status updates, and cancellations.
FR4.3
Vendor Notifications
The system shall send push notifications to vendors for new orders, order modifications, and customer inquiries.
FR4.4
Consumer Messaging
The system shall provide an in-app messaging feature for consumers to communicate with vendors regarding specific orders.
FR4.5
Vendor Messaging
The system shall provide an in-app messaging feature for vendors to communicate with consumers regarding specific orders.
FR4.6
Email Notifications
The system shall send email notifications for critical account-related activities (e.g., password reset, account verification).



4.5 System Feature 5: Rating and Review System

Req ID
Requirement
Description
FR5.1
Ratings
The system shall allow consumers to rate vendors and individual meals after an order has been completed.
FR5.2
Reviews
The system shall allow consumers to write text reviews for vendors and meals.
FR5.3
Display Reviews
The system shall display average ratings and reviews for vendors and meals to other consumers.
FR5.4
Vendor Responses
The system shall allow vendors to respond to consumer reviews.
FR5.5
Moderation
The system shall implement a moderation process for reviews to prevent abusive or inappropriate content.

5. Nonfunctional Requirements
Req ID
Requirement
Description
NFR1.1
Response Time
The system shall respond to user requests (e.g., loading meal listings, processing orders) within 3 seconds under normal load conditions.
NFR1.2
Scalability
The system shall be able to support up to 1,000 concurrent users and process 100 orders per minute without significant degradation in performance.
NFR1.3
Availability
The system shall be available 99.9% of the time, excluding scheduled maintenance.
NFR1.4
Throughput
The system shall be capable of handling a minimum of 50 transactions per second during peak hours.


5.2 Safety Requirements
Req ID
Requirement
Description
NFR2.1
Food Safety
The system shall require vendors to confirm adherence to local food safety standards before listing meals.
NFR2.2
Allergen Information
The system shall provide fields for vendors to list common allergens present in meals, and allow consumers to filter by allergen information.
NFR2.3
Safe Handling
The system shall provide guidelines for safe food handling and pickup/delivery practices for vendors.


5.3 Security Requirements

Req ID
Requirement
Description
NFR3.1
Data Encryption
All sensitive user data (e.g., passwords, payment information) shall be encrypted both in transit (SSL/TLS) and at rest (AES-256 or higher).
NFR3.2
Authentication
The system shall implement multi-factor authentication (MFA) for vendor accounts and optionally for consumer accounts.
NFR3.3
Authorization
The system shall ensure that users can only access data and perform actions for which they have explicit permissions.
NFR3.4
Payment Security
The system shall comply with PCI DSS standards for handling payment card information or rely on PCI-compliant third-party payment gateways.
NFR3.5
Vulnerability Management
Regular security audits and penetration testing shall be conducted to identify and address vulnerabilities.


Software Quality Attributes


Req ID
Requirement
Description
NFR4.1
Usability
The mobile applications shall have an intuitive and easy-to-learn interface, requiring minimal training.
NFR4.2
Maintainability
The codebase shall be well-documented, modular, and follow established coding standards.
NFR4.3
Portability
The mobile applications shall be compatible with major versions of Android and iOS, and the web application shall be accessible across modern browsers.
NFR4.4
Reliability
The system shall minimize data loss and provide robust error handling mechanisms.
NFR4.5
Testability
The system shall be designed to allow comprehensive and automated testing of all requirements.


Business Rules


Req ID
Requirement
Description
BR1.1
Discount Policy
All meals listed on ChopNow must be offered at a discount of at least 20% off their original price.
BR1.2
Vendor Payouts
Vendors shall receive payouts for completed orders within 24–48 hours, minus a platform service fee.
BR1.3
Order Cancellation
Consumers can cancel orders before the vendor accepts them without penalty. After acceptance, cancellations may incur a fee or be subject to vendor discretion.
BR1.4
Meal Expiry
Vendors must specify a pickup time window, and meals not picked up within this window may be forfeited without refund.
BR1.5
Geographic Scope
The platform will initially operate in selected urban areas within specific African countries.


6. Appendix
Appendix A: Glossary
ChopNow: The digital platform for food rescue and affordable meals. Consumer: A user who purchases discounted surplus meals from vendors.
Vendor: A local food business (restaurant, bakery, etc.) that sells surplus meals on ChopNow.
SRS: Software Requirements Specification.
MVP: Minimum Viable Product.
API: Application Programming Interface.
UI: User Interface.
UX: User Experience.
FAO: Food and Agriculture Organization.
WFP: World Food Program.
Agile: An iterative and incremental approach to software development.
Functional Requirement (FR): A requirement that specifies a function that a system or component must be able to perform.
Non-Functional Requirement (NFR): A requirement that specifies criteria that can be used to judge the operation of a system, rather than specific behaviors (e.g., performance, security).
Appendix B: Analysis Models
This section will include diagrams such as Use Case Diagrams, Class Diagrams, Activity Diagrams, and Data Flow Diagrams to visually represent the system's architecture and functionality. These diagrams will be generated in a subsequent phase.
Appendix B: Analysis Models
This section provides visual representations of the ChopNow system's architecture and functionality through various diagrams.
Use Case Diagram
The Use Case Diagram illustrates the interactions between the primary actors (Consumer, Vendor, Payment Gateway, and Mapping Service) and the ChopNow system. It delineates the main functionalities offered by the platform from the perspective of its users, providing a high-level overview of the system's scope and behavior.

Class Diagram
The Class Diagram presents the static structure of the ChopNow system, showcasing the main classes, their attributes, methods, and relationships. This diagram is crucial for understanding the system's data model and how different components interact at a conceptual level.
Activity Diagram: Order Placement
The Activity Diagram for Order Placement visualizes the workflow of a consumer placing an order and a vendor managing it. It details the sequence of activities, decisions, and parallel processes involved in the core functionality of the ChopNow platform, from meal browsing to order completion.

Sequence Diagram


The Sequence Diagram for ChopNow illustrates how different components of the system interact step-by-step when a consumer places an order for a discounted meal. It focuses on the communication flow between the user interface, backend services, vendor system, payment gateway, and database.gateways, and mapping services.